{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T20:53:12.505913+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 65 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 78 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":78,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":65,"completed_with_unit_data":65,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":27,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2643,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 65 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -26.4%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":482,"p25":-0.4838,"median":-0.2643,"p75":-0.02},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.0544,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 65 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +5.4%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":65,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":65,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.2339,"mean":0.1376,"median":0.0544,"p25":-0.085,"p50":0.0544,"p75":0.2692,"p10":-0.1931,"p90":0.5338},"median_actual_dollars":240637.46},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~117 hours per plumbing unit","value":117.3519,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 117.4 hrs/unit (P25 100, P75 138). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 100 and 138 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":65,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":123.5238,"median":117.3519,"p25":100.2083,"p50":117.3519,"p75":137.8056,"p10":78.5912,"p90":159.2063,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.7%","value":0.3868,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.7%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":65,"p25":0.3132,"median":0.3868,"p75":0.4544},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$44.42/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":44.4245,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $44.42/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":30.7042,"loaded_wage_median":44.4245,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4232},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.7% median)","value":-0.1572,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.7%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":613,"min":-0.9914,"max":4.6293,"mean":-0.0975,"median":-0.1572,"p25":-0.4132,"p50":-0.1572,"p75":0.0901,"p10":-0.6055,"p90":0.4279},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":65,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":123.5238,"median":117.3519,"p25":100.2083,"p50":117.3519,"p75":137.8056,"p10":78.5912,"p90":159.2063,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":65,"min":359.0298,"max":11628.9416,"mean":3662.4666,"median":3631.7984,"p25":2915.9517,"p50":3631.7984,"p75":4214.5645,"p10":1954.0082,"p90":5057.4223,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":65,"min":1219.6971,"max":9672.2479,"mean":3775.3591,"median":3778.6547,"p25":2926.2036,"p50":3778.6547,"p75":4408.2127,"p10":2096.9417,"p90":5095.0032,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":65,"min":7181.5,"max":41985.5421,"mean":16038.6594,"median":16157.602,"p25":12807.0,"p50":16157.602,"p75":18691.0694,"p10":10187.615,"p90":20933.5418,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":65,"min":0.0157,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2299,"median":0.225,"p25":0.2053,"p50":0.225,"p75":0.2642,"p10":0.1849,"p90":0.2869,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":65,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2353,"median":0.2346,"p25":0.2161,"p50":0.2346